  "body": "Buyers in Dubai paid an average premium of 64% for branded units compared to non-branded homes in the first nine months of 2025, according to CBRE's UAE Branded Residence Report, underscoring the structural repricing of the emirate's luxury segment as global wealth migration accelerates and developers pivot toward hospitality-managed typologies.\n\nTransaction values increased 51% year-on-year in the nine-month period, even as volumes rose 26% — a compression that signals larger average ticket sizes and a decisive shift toward ultra-prime assets. The data confirms that branded residences, once a niche product, now represent a mandate for developers targeting high-net-worth individuals who view real estate as a managed lifestyle allocation rather than a speculative play.\n\nHospitality-branded residences typically command a price premium of 30% to 40% over comparable unbranded stock, with the gap widening in the most sought-after locations, said Zeeshan Shah, CEO and Founder of Elevate. That range, however, understates the premium in certain precincts: branded residences in Abu Dhabi command an average premium of 87%, reflecting both scarcity and the appeal of globally renowned hospitality and lifestyle brands, while Aman Residences reached AED 13,195 per square foot, setting a new benchmark for ultra-luxury pricing in the UAE.\n\nThe premium is not cosmetic. Branded residences are homes linked to a recognised hotel, hospitality or lifestyle brand, with buyers receiving a private residence alongside the service standards, design, management and amenities usually associated with hotels. That can include concierge services, housekeeping, security, wellness facilities, branded interiors, rental management and access to hospitality benefits — a turnkey proposition that appeals to globally mobile buyers who require lock-and-leave functionality and institutional-grade property management.\n\nAs of 2025, Dubai boasts the highest number of branded residence schemes in the world, with approximately 140 projects either completed or in the pipeline, and the city now commands 48,474 branded residence units across 132 completed projects. Over 31,000 branded units are planned for delivery in Dubai by 2030, a pipeline that will test absorption capacity but also reflects developer confidence in sustained demand from the 9,800 new millionaires forecast to relocate to the UAE in 2025, the highest net inflow of high-net-worth individuals globally.\n\n\"The UAE has undergone a structural shift,\" said Zeeshan Shah. \"This is no longer a market driven by speculation or short-term capital. What we're witnessing is the relocation of global wealth, with families, founders, and sophisticated investors choosing the UAE as their primary base.\" That thesis is borne out by rental-yield data: gross rental yields for branded luxury residences range from 6 to 8% in Palm Jumeirah, Downtown, and Business Bay, while rental rates in Dubai Hills and Palm Jebel Ali run 15–25% higher than comparable non-branded units.\n\nThe segment's composition is evolving. Branded residences with hotel management now represent 38% of all branded developments, increasingly preferred by HNWIs seeking privacy and five-star service, while non-hospitality brands — automotive marques such as Bugatti, Mercedes-Benz, and Bentley, alongside fashion houses like Armani and Bulgari — are claiming market share in the ultra-luxury villa segment. Bugatti Residences by Binghatti was ranked the most expensive branded residence in Dubai in 2025, a reflection of the scarcity premium attached to automotive-branded inventory.\n\nGeographically, supply remains concentrated in established luxury precincts. Downtown Dubai hosts 21 branded projects, Business Bay 17, and Palm Jumeirah 16, though emerging destinations are gaining traction: the branded-residence segment's share of new supply deliveries in Abu Dhabi is projected to reach 18% during 2029, supported by landmark projects on Saadiyat and Yas Islands.\n\nThe investment case rests on three pillars: scarcity, service infrastructure, and secondary-market liquidity. Resale gains of 20–25% are expected at premium locations, while global research indicates that branded residences achieve around a 30–33% premium over comparable non-branded property, while also holding value better during downturns. That resilience reflects the segment's appeal to end-users rather than flippers: 79% of branded residence transactions were off-plan, reflecting demand from international investors seeking flexible payment plans, lower entry prices, and access to new, design-led communities.\n\nMacroeconomic tailwinds remain supportive. UAE GDP growth is forecast at 5.3% in 2025, supported by diversification into non-oil sectors and sustained investor confidence, while the Golden Visa programme — which grants 10-year renewable residency to buyers of properties valued at AED 2 million or more — continues to anchor demand from sovereign-wealth-adjacent buyers and family offices seeking tax-efficient domiciles.\n\nThe risk, as always, lies in oversupply. With the branded residences market in Dubai estimated at USD 10.8 billion and dozens of launches scheduled through 2028, absorption will depend on the emirate's ability to sustain HNWI inflows at current levels. For now, however, the data suggests that branded residences have transitioned from a speculative niche to a structural component of Dubai's ultra-prime market — a repricing driven not by hype, but by the institutionalisation of lifestyle as an asset class.",
